# erToK: ER ‚Üí K^sim_2 via zero-test URM simulation

The compiler half of the erToK construction: emit a
`URMProgram` from an `ERMor1 a` term such that running the
URM long enough produces `e.interp v` in the output
register.

## Main definitions

- `URMInstrRaw`: ‚Ñï-indexed instruction intermediate used
  by compiler combinators before the final register-count
  is known.
- `URMInstrRaw.toBounded`: total conversion from a raw
  instruction to a `URMInstr r`, given a bound proof on
  every register index appearing in the raw instruction.
- `CompiledFragment`: a self-contained compiled URM
  fragment extending `URMProgram a` with a reserved-zero
  register convention used to encode unconditional
  `goto`.
- `CompiledFragment.toURMProgram`: auto-generated by the
  `extends URMProgram a` clause; forgets the reserved-zero
  fields and returns the underlying `URMProgram a`.
- `compileFrag_zero`, `compileFrag_succ`,
  `compileFrag_proj`, `compileFrag_sub`: atomic
  per-ER-constructor fragment combinators (no
  sub-fragment composition).
- `compileFrag_comp`: compositional combinator for
  `ERMor1.comp f gs` ‚Äî glues sub-fragments via raw-level
  register-space injection and PC-shifting (fused into
  `URMInstrRaw.reindexShift`) and destructive output‚Üíinput
  transfer between sub-fragments.
- `compileFrag_bsum`: compositional combinator for
  `ERMor1.bsum f` ‚Äî outer loop on the bound register
  with per-iteration prologue re-cloning outer
  parameters and accumulator update via transferLoop.
- `compileFrag_bprod`: compositional combinator for
  `ERMor1.bprod f` ‚Äî mirrors `compileFrag_bsum` with a
  multiplicative accumulator (initial value 1) updated
  via Tourlakis 2018 p. 19's R^XY_Z nested-loop
  template.
- `compileER`: the top-level recursive driver
  `{a : ‚Ñï} ‚Üí ERMor1 a ‚Üí URMProgram a`. Dispatches to
  the per-constructor combinators via `compileERFrag`
  and forgets the reserved-zero convention via
  `.toURMProgram`.
- `compileER_runtime`: ‚Ñï-valued runtime witness defined
  by structural recursion on `e`; sufficient step count
  for `URMState.runFor (compileER e) v` to halt with
  output register holding `e.interp v`.

